map_node.indicator_name: Carbon Monoxide Incidents without a Detector (3 Year Avg.)
map_node.indicator_description: Carbon monoxide detectors are required in NYC homes by law. Failure to provide or maintain a detector can put residents at risk for carbon monoxide poisoning and death.

dataset.how_calculated: A 3-year average annual rate of carbon monoxide incidents where FDNY measured at least 1 ppm at the scene, and there was no detector (alarm) or alarm did not go off; expressed as incidents per 10,000 buildings.
dataset.discription: Fire Department of New York City (FDNY) Carbon Monoxide Incidents

show_disparities_node.disparitiesPagetext: When population health or the quality of living environments varies by population characteristics such as income or race, there is disparity. One way to visualize disparity is to chart indicators of health or environment across levels of neighborhood poverty. We categorized neighborhoods as high, medium or low poverty. Then we took the median of the neighborhood-specific values in each category. The median is the middle of the sorted group of values.
